    <p style="font-size: 0.85rem; color: #6c757d; margin-top: 0.5rem; text-align: center;">
      Video: Shenzhen's cashier-less stores.
    </p>
    
    <p>I walked into a convenience store in Shanghai at 11 PM. No staff at the counter. Just a small sign: “Scan to enter. Scan to pay. See you next time.”</p>

    <p>I swiped my phone against the door, it clicked open, and I walked in. Nobody greeted me. Nobody followed me around. Just me and a hundred shelves of snacks, drinks, and instant noodles.</p>

    <p>I grabbed a bottle of iced tea and a pack of spicy tofu. When I walked to the exit, a screen lit up, automatically scanning my items. I held my phone against the scanner — a payment of 12 yuan went through. The door opened, and I walked out.</p>

    <p>Total time: four minutes. Words exchanged: zero.</p>

    <p>I tried it again the next night, just to see if it was real. Same thing. No cashier, no line, no small talk.</p>

    <p>Later, I read that these stores use over a hundred cameras to track every item and every person. It sounds like surveillance, but it feels like trust.</p>

    <p>In my country, convenience stores have three employees on shift and still get robbed. Here, nobody even watches the door. And somehow, it works.</p>


